hands_on_practices.problem:
A semi-infinite elastic string is stretched along the positive x-axis, from $x=0$ to infinity. The end at $x=0$ is attached to a small, massless ring that can slide without friction on a vertical rod, which constitutes a free boundary (Neumann boundary condition). The propagation speed of transverse waves on the string is given as $c = 200$ m/s. The string is initially at rest. At time $t=0$, the string is given an initial displacement described by the function:
$$
u(x, 0) = f(x) =
\begin{cases}
    A_0 \left( 1 - \left( \frac{x-x_c}{W} \right)^2 \right)  \text{for } |x - x_c| \leq W \\
    0  \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
$$
where the amplitude is $A_0 = 0.0500$ m, the center of the pulse is $x_c = 100$ m, and the half-width is $W = 20.0$ m. The initial velocity of the string is zero everywhere.

Determine the transverse displacement of the string at the position $x = 50.0$ m at time $t = 0.700$ s. Express your answer in meters, rounded to three significant figures.
